Tu‘i’ilnn Increase
president suggest announced Friday a
$175.00 increase in fees for the 1969—70
academic year, bringing the total compreliensive fee for one year at Grinnell
to $3,275. Tuition has increased from
$2,125 to $2,270, This amount, in accordance with the Trustees' policy, covers
approximately two-things of the actual
educational Cast for each student, Other
increases from costs of food and health
services will also be made, modeling an
additional $30.
In a letter to Grinnell parents President suggest explained the major reasons for the increases along with a
general forecast of the financial situation. He said, “The major reasons for
the increases are (l) the continuing ins
sense competition for and the rising
salaries or highly qualified scholar
teachers, and (2) higher state wages and
student labor wages, together with the
general inflation of costs. These red‘
sons are of course not unique to Grinnell.
All colleges and universities, public and
private, are facing financial problems.
This is indicated by the fact that among
the to colleges beginning to the associated Colleges of the Midwest (of which
Grinnell is one), the projected increases
in comprehensive charges for next year
range from $160 to $405, with an average
or $227 per institution.
"We expect a very substantial in«
create in operating costs for 1969-70.
