Truth in Packaging
The KRNT television special on Grinnell began with some
stock footage of long-failed, widely participating college students
throwing things and shooting God knows What. A campus root, in
other words. It went on to show approximately 10 minutes of
what could just as well have been stock footage: a “responsible”
picture of student life exemplified by Gl‘innell College. My argument with the program is based not on whether or not Grinnell
life is responsible, but rather that the show served simply as an—
other 3x5 card in that catalogued, categorized index of clothes
“images” which the program was supposedly intended to disney.
There is nothing Wrong, and a good deal right, with such
wholesale Grinnell activities as Uncle Sam’s Club, inter-racial
house, CBS’s playing basketball, AWARE, or scholarship winners.
But in attempting to present this as a true picture of Grinnell
life—and thereby in effect generating equally important aspects
of student life such as discretion and projects to the position of
campus opportunities—somehow, a great difference is done to
both the college community and to the public in general. After
all, the numbers of students involved in'each of the wholesale
activities is a minority of the student body, just as those who
participated in the listening incident were. To designers some
priorities as “the way today’s students really are,” and others
FREDRICKA NELSON talking with her neighbor Vanesa.
talk of the town
as “a loudspoken but unrepresentative fridge,” is not only a discretion of the truth but a displaying interpretation as well.
I hope the college administration is not as pleased with the
program as I imagine they very well may be. Mr, suggest spoke
the other night of the need for diversity on Grinnell’s campus,
but this program seemed to belle
students on this campus, individuals,
that appeal. There are many
who find different ways to
participate in campus life. To select any molecular group of indi—
signals as representative of the entire student body is both un-
fair and announced, whether they be
clean-cut or not. If river-
site is the call, let’s not try to jump all students into an homogen-
ized, british-free
product for public consumption. Let’s con~
since to provide pictures of campus life such as the KRNT program, which was accurate even if clothes, but at the same time
let‘s provide the whole
picture. And if the public comes knock-
ing on our door looking for the picture of a typical middle-class,
synthetic, self-centered student, let us have the poverty to say,
“I’m sorry, you’ve come to the wrong place.” '
 
