assistant Prof. of Political Science
Discussions wondering the recent
campus listening incident usually focus
upon the notices of the actors involved.
The students are accused of being public.
ltd-hungry, the attorney general is infected for his alleged desire for political
gain, and the local protection is accused
of a weeks-speed cancellation to political
message. 0n the basis of such dishes
signs it is easy to large into ad hominum
arguments about these participants. (Indeed, is certain local cement mixer
whose humor reflects all the subtlety of
an amplifier front sheer, has developed
this ad hominum approach into a likely
honey, if continuously and awkwardly
used method.)-chess rather parochial
discussions fail to consider some of the
most important aspects of the issue, Two
questions are particularly appropriate
and interesting, First, what makes the
issue so performing to the public? Second,
why is the settlement of the issue specially so dependent upon the legal pro«
less?
A common response. to the first ques<
tion might very well be, “Only an act<
decision could ask such a questions
The reason is simply that people don’t
like students running around without
their clothes on." I suggest that the issue is a more complex issue which is
related to some basic social and political characteristics of American society.
Public opinion surveys quite conclusively
show that very few Americans have anything close to a well deﬁnew, well developed political theology. Nonetheless,
most of us manifest some kind of basic
and quite stable core oi corrections and
attitudes which we use to interview the
world around us. The visiting incident
