The Gllnnell art department is not as
old as it could be. it is under-stuffed.
glhkil‘fg it Impossible for nonrmajors to
take courses, and it is di adult for motors
to pursue their education. The department packs scope in the introductory as
well as advanced courses. In the case
of a leave of absence, there is no effort
(trade to hire a temporary replacement.
t the introductory level, the department sometimes designs a man realized only for studio instruction to an art
istory class. As a result, the quality of
instruction is poor in the course, and he
is unable to teach a studio course for
which he is qualified. Art motors are not
‘fly limited by the courses, but also by
‘he eight credit restriction on indexed
sent study.
With’these problems in mind. the art
motors held a consortium last week—
and to organize themselves and make
suggestions on how to improve the de-
comment.
r The consortium recommended the animation of two new staff members, one in
art; history and one ill the studio inspection.
They all decided to calculate a ques
tionnaire in hopes of determining how
bunny “non-motors" have been unable to
take courses and workshops. The motors
will be asked to put down in writing the
courses they feel are necessary for their
education.
The colloquim also decided to go to
Chicago on April 4—7 where they will
visit Chicago art schools and museums,
‘the motors are also trying to make arrangements for an underground film
series. The main obstacle to both the trip
and the movies is money; as the art department's budget does not provide
enough money for extracurricular activities. The money will have to come from
the students.
